(BTW, both of these character types are really popular and relatable now-a-days, but they'll pretend "No one understands them! They are unique outcast, like YOU, viewer! Don't you feel special, 259,087th viewer?") Â  And guess what: they don't get along at first! But then, she grows to endear him and his moronic ignorant head-first nature, and she giggle endearingly as he ignored all common sense, most likely because she hasn't had proper human contact in quite a while. This will eventually lead to a scene where she pretends to feel betrayed, because mean bad guy get involved.Â  I don't mean to offend anyone who genuinely likes this, and is looking forward to it, and I don't care if it's based of a book. text: Spoiler           The movie was okay.   Had weird pacing problems and a few plot holes, the whole friendship development between Tip and Boov wasnt fleshed out.  Halfway through the movie Boov does something drastic and Tip who is barely getting along with Boov at this point gets overly distraught.  It was like any real friendship development was off screen, only implied.  Way too many "look I'm trying to be funny gags".  The movie is perfect for little kids who don't really care for pacing and and character development but as an adult there are far too few laughs and touching moments.  The visuals are cool though.

text: I saw this film and have mixed feelings. There were some things I really loved: some of the jokes were brilliant and very clever; I really liked the ethnic diversity portrayed in the movie as a whole; I also really liked the way women were depicted having a pear shape instead of the usual super skinny models; the main character had a refreshing and relatively original personality, and I liked the emphasis on her intellect. Also, some parts made me tearful with emotion, and the characters were voiced by an all-star cast. Tip's hair was beautiful! The things I didn't like so much: I felt like some of the plot points were predictable; some of the insights felt cliched and trite; it also felt like they were trying to fit as many Rihanna songs into this movie as they could, which to me felt a bit forced. I'd still recommend it, it was a cool film.

text: I gotta say the trailer for this blew me away, and I want to talk about one joke in particular  See, the main character, Sheldon Cooper,is not from Earth. He's from an alien planet, so he doesn't understand things that happen on Earth and human design. So there's one bit where Sheldon Cooper is on Earth with Rihanna and they're in a car that Rihanna can drive and while in the car they stop at a gas stop on go into the toilet in the gas stop on Earth. And Sheldon Cooper is talking to Rihanna through the wall of the bathroom because they're in different bathrooms in the toilets in the gas stop on Earth and Sheldon Cooper says to Rihanna he says "They have bowls of lemonade here!". Now that is the set up for the joke I am talking about, the line "They have bowls of lemonade" is part one of a two part joke the second part of which comes immediately after. See just after Sheldon Cooper talks about the bowls of lemonade to Rihanna he attempts to drink the lemonade at which point he exclaims through the wall of the toilet of the gas stop on Earth to Rihanna that "the yellow liquid is not lemonade!" and that is part two of the joke and is the punchline and the payoff for part one of the joke that I mentioned earlier.  The joke is that aliens shouldn't know what lemonade is so the fact that Sheldon Cooper knows about lemonade is mysterious and hilarious.
